<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="73" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="73">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="73">
The specific epithet refers to the apparent epiphytic habit of the species, though, like other species in the genus, 
<taxonomicName genus="D." lsidName="D. epifita" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" rank="species" species="epifita">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">D. epifita</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a hemiepiphyte rather than an obligate epiphyte.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="73" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="73">Specimens examined.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="73">
<materialsCitation collectingDate="1968-06-25" collectingDateMax="2016-03-12" collectingDateMin="1968-06-25" collectorName="de Sardinayacu, Freire, Cerda, Canton El Chaco, Punto ST, la Reserva Pindo" country="Ecuador" county="Belen de Los Andaquies" elevation="1450" latitude="-1.4997222" location="Acevedo" longLatPrecision="21" longitude="-78.062225" municipality="Andaqui" specimenCount="1" stateProvince="Morona-Santiago">
